## What I Learned:
- Ports (65535 total, 1024 well-known) direct traffic to applications
- SYN scan (-sS) is "half-open" or "stealth" and requires sudo
- Closed TCP ports respond with RST flag (RFC 793)
- UDP ports that don't respond are marked "open|filtered"
- NULL, FIN, Xmas scans evade firewalls; Windows responds with RST to all
- NSE scripts are written in Lua; "intrusive" category is dangerous in production
- Firewall evasion: -Pn (skip ICMP), --data-length (add random data)
- Practical scan results: Xmas scan showed 999 open/filtered (no response), SYN scan showed 5 open ports, FTP anonymous login succeeded

## Summary:
Nmap is a network scanner for host discovery, port scanning, service/OS detection, and vulnerability detection.
This room covered scan types (SYN, TCP, UDP, NULL, FIN, Xmas, ICMP), NSE scripts (Lua, categories like intrusive), firewall evasion, timing templates, and practical scanning.
